t4997.text: And we’re driving on the Nullarbor. And we can’t buy a new car. And we can’t call for a tow truck when we run out of juice. We’re on our own. And the people who are telling us to just drive for another year or ten are not the ones who will have to get out and push.

t4998.text: This: in the late 19th and early 20th century Australia stuck with an outdated horse-and-buggy economy for 50 years, and working people suffered and we became a backwater. Our trusty diesel economy is as outmoded now as our horse-and-buggy was then.

t4999.text: You have to build your economic vehicle yourself. That means every year Australia keeps driving its diesel without planning for ways to convert the old clapper to hybrid, then electric, is another year wasted. What am I saying?

t5000.text: You see, I know that I asked you to think of the Australian economy like a car, but, in reality, economies are not like cars. They’re not, because you can’t just trade in your diesel for aN electric. You can’t just buy the future off the shelf. You have to build it.

t5001.text: That’s right, our diesel will no longer get us where we need to go and Australia will be standing on the side of the road in some economic Nullarbor. What’s the answer? Keep driving the diesel until we run out of juice? Bad idea. Let me tell you why.

t5003.text: Not only that, pretty soon (as soon as 2024), the price of the fuel that runs our diesel economy will either be unavailable or so expensive (due to global pricing of carbon and the dearth of private money for carbon industries) that our trust diesel will run out of juice.

t5004.text: Just like our horse and buggy was left behind by global diesels in the 50 years from the 1890s to the 1940s, our trusty diesel is starting to struggle. It can’t compete with the hybrid and electric economies that are hooning past.

t5005.text: We love our national set of wheels. It’s taken us from an industrial backwater (Australia’s economy was a horse-and-buggy up until WW2) to one of the wealthiest countries in the world. But times have changed.

t5006.text: Want to know why Australia’s inaction on climate change is bad for everyone, especially the working families looking for a way out of carbon-intensive sectors like coal? Think of the national economy like a car. Australia’s vehicle is a tough diesel, circa 1948. #auspol
